<HEADLINE>
<P>
REDSKINS PERFECTLY AWFUL AT HOME; NFC: THEY END UP WITHOUT A VICTORY AT RFK 
STADIUM FOR THE FIRST TIME AS TAMPA BAY INCREASES WINNING STREAK TO FOUR. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Washington Redskins are struggling through the kind of season usually 
endured by the Tampa Bay Buccaneers. 
</P>
<P>
 Washington wound up winless at home for the first time in franchise history, 
losing to Tampa Bay, 17-14, Sunday on Errict Rhett's three-yard touchdown run 
with seven minutes left. 
</P>
<P>
 The Buccaneers (6-9) won their fourth consecutive game, their longest winning 
streak since starting out 5-0 in 1978. They can avoid their 12th consecutive 
season of double-digit losses with a victory next week at home against Green 
Bay. 
</P>
<P>
 The Redskins (2-13), meanwhile, finished 0-8 at RFK Stadium, where there were 
9,097 no-shows on a sunny, 50-degree day. 
</P>
<P>
 Washington, in its first year under Coach Norv Turner, set a team record for 
most losses in a season. The Redskins also dropped their seventh in a row, 
their longest losing streak since 1964-65. 
</P>
<P>
 "My whole approach to this is that we are going to continue to get better on a 
weekly basis, on a monthly basis, on a yearly basis, and we'll find a way to 
win close ballgames and we'll win a lot of games," Turner said. 
</P>
<P>
 For the eighth time this season, Washington lost a game in which it led in the 
second half. Tampa Bay got the winning touchdown after Vernon Turner returned a 
punt 37 yards and Erickson threw a 13-yard pass to Scott Armstrong. 
</P>
<P>
 Rhett, who stung the Redskins two weeks ago by running for 192 yards in a 
26-21 victory, was held to only 64 yards in 23 carries. But quarterback Craig 
Erickson finished 19 for 34 for 267 yards with two interceptions. 
</P>
<P>
 "They just did a good job (defending the run)," Tampa Bay Coach Sam Wyche 
said. "We decided we had to throw the ball." 
</P>
<P>
 The Redskins did not score in the second half. They had a chance to extend a 
14-10 lead at the end of the third quarter, but Heath Shuler's third-down pass 
from the Tampa Bay 27 went through Henry Ellard's outstretched arms, and Chip 
Lohmiller missed a 44-yard kick on the next play. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Game Story; Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA121994-0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 109507 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
