SOUTHLAND PREVIEW / THE BUSINESS WEEK AHEAD: LOS ANGELES COUNTY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Telephone Line: State regulators are expected to set the ground rules 
Wednesday for competition in local telephone markets, which are now monopolies 
for Pacific Bell and General Telephone Co. of California. This is part of the 
Public Utilities Commission's plan to revamp the state's telecommunications 
industry to introduce competition in all markets.Among other issues, the 
commissioners will look at changing the definition of basic phone service and 
how to pay for universal service for low-income and elderly customers. The rule 
changes will let such giants as AT&T and MCI compete for strictly local phone 
business. The PUC, which has already opened up the market for so-called local 
long-distance as of Jan. 1, hopes to deregulate the rest of the industry within 
two years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
