<HEADLINE>
<P>
PACIFIC WATCH: JAPAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Trade Barriers Cost Consumers, Study Says: According to a study by the 
Institute for International Economics, the trade barriers that keep foreign 
goods out of Japan cost consumers as much as $110 billion in 1989 (or as much 
as $150 billion at current exchange rates) but enrich Japanese companies, 
making it politically difficult to dismantle them. The study says that Japanese 
consumers are starting to realize that food and clothing are far more expensive 
in Tokyo than in New York and that they are beginning to complain about 
practices that keep less-expensive imports off the shelves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
