<HEADLINE>
<P>
PACIFIC WATCH: INDONESIA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Indonesia Revokes Forest Concessions: In an action seen as a move toward 
curbing excessive logging and bad management of its tropical forests, the 
country has revoked 75 forest concessions of an unknown number of firms, the 
Antara news agency said.Warsito, secretary of the directorate-general of Forest 
Exploitation, said Forestry Minister Djamaluddin Soeryohadikusumo made the 
decision after 135 concessions expired. Most of those had run for 20 years. 
Warsito was quoted as saying state companies would take equity in another 33 
concessions. Antara said a total of 580 forest concessions had been issued 
since 1970. 
</P>
</TEXT>
