<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS FOCUS: NEWPORT BEACH; PLAN TO CURB LOUD PARTIES GAINS SUPPORT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By HOLLY J. WAGNER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Residents appear to be in support of the city's impending party ordinance, 
which would use fines to curtail loud parties in the city. 
</P>
<P>
 Only six residents attended an informational meeting last week to discuss the 
measure and all of them favored the new controls, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
 Police Sgt. Andy Gonis acknowledged that the ordinance is being discussed 
during the city's off-season, when visitors who rent homes are not yet in town. 
</P>
<P>
 "Most of the people who are renting at this time of year are long-term 
leases," he said, adding the ordinance is designed precisely to protect those 
people. 
</P>
<P>
 "It is going to deter those (renters) who come down here simply to take 
advantage of others," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 The ordinance, tentatively approved by the City Council last week, is expected 
to get final approval in January.  
</P>
<P>
 Currently, the city bills the tenants of "party houses" $150 if police have to 
go to the same address more than once in 30 days to quiet loud parties. Under 
the new ordinance, fines would rise to $250 for the second party call within a 
year, to $500 for the third call and $750 for the fourth and any subsequent 
calls. 
</P>
<P>
 Despite the stiff fines, police maintained they are not looking at the measure 
as way to raise revenue.  
</P>
<P>
 "We're not hoping to generate money," Gonis said. "What we're hoping to do is 
end the party problem." 
</P>
<P>
 Residents of west Newport, where police traditionally have had to answer the 
bulk of complaints about loud parties, requested the controls to curtail 
rowdiness and noise, he said. 
</P>
<P>
 The police have enlisted the aid of rental agents and property management 
agencies to inform tenants, especially week-to-week renters who visit between 
Memorial Day and Labor Day, of the penalties if parties get out of hand, Gonis 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 The ordinance would also gives officers some discretion in applying the 
penalties when answering party-call complaints, he said. 
</P>
<P>
 "What one person calls just having a good time may be a tremendous irritant to 
someone else," Gonis said. HOLLY J. WAGNER 
</P>
</TEXT>
